        <h2>Build your own dipole antenna - 2m and 70cm</h2>

<h3>Introduction</h3>
As the antenna is a major part of my hobby - Ham Radio, I wanted to understand how it works. 
Started to read about E and H fields, impedance and polarization gain and much more - interesting but tiring over time. 
So I started to build my own antenna and learned on the way. Much more rewarding.
<br>
Started with planning. <br><br>
<strong>My project list: </strong>
<ol type="1">
  <li>What frequency do I need to use for 2m and 70 cm</li>
  <li>Dipole antenna length</li>
  <li>Tools</li>
  <li>Material list</li>
  <li>Build antenna</li>
</ol>
<br>
<h3 class='scout-h3'>1. Calculate Frequency</h3>
<p>
The math for calculating the frequency in words: <br>
<strong>Frequency is equal to the speed of light divided by the wavelength. </strong>
</p>
<p class='scout-indend-1'><strong>2m:</strong> f<sub>(2m)</sub> = 300*10<sup>3</sup>[m/s] / 2m = 150Mhz</p>
<p class='scout-indend-1'><strong>70cm:</strong> f<sub>(70cm)</sub> = 300*10<sup>3</sup>[m/s] / 0.7m = 428.5MHz</p>
<p>
A dipole should be used for around a frequency of 3KHz to 300GHz. My frequencies of f=150MHz for 2m and 
f=428.5MHz for 70cm are suitable for a dipole antenna.
</p>
Please note that &lambda; is used in literature for the wavelength. &lambda = c/f<br>
<br>
<h3 class='scout-h3'>2. Dipole antenna length</h3>
<p>
A dipole antenna is built by a conducting wire which is half wavelength long. The feeding (voltage) of the 
dipole antenna is in the middle of the antenna. The reason for that is that the impedance falls to its lowest 
in the middle. <br>Please also consider that the wavelength is slightly shorter in conductors than in plain
air.
</p>
<p class='scout-indend-1'><strong>2m:</strong> f<sub>(2m)</sub> = Quarter wave length * full wave length = ¼ * 2m = 0.5m = 50cm = <strong>19.58 inches</strong>
</p>
<p class='scout-indend-1'><strong>70cm:</strong> f<sub>(70cm)</sub> = Quarter wave length * full wave length = ¼ * 0.7m = 17.5cm = <strong>6.88 inches</strong>
</p><br><br>

<h4><strong><u>Choose your frequency in 2m band</u></strong></h4>
<p>The 2 meter band is from f<sub>(low)</sub> = 144MHz to f<sub>(high)</sub> = 148MHz.<br> 
    <strong>My antenna should have a low Standing Wave Ratio (SWR) at f = 146MHz.</strong> <br>
    That is based on to have a wider frequency range of usable channels up and down the spectrum [(144+148)MHz / 2 = 146MHz]
</p>
<ol>
  <li>Wavelength of f=146MHz leads to a wavelength: &lambda;(<sub>146MHz</sub>)
  =300*10<sup>3</sup>[m/s] / 146*10<sup>3</sup>[1/s]= <strong>2.054m</strong></li>
  <li>Quarter wavelength in meters: 2.054m / 4 = <strong>0.5136m</strong></li>
  <li>Length of the each dipole arm is: 0.5136m * 39.37 = <strong>20.22 inches</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>
  The calculated length per antenna arm is 20.22 inches but please consider that this value
  is a theoretical value and as mentioned above it is for the air. The used wire material, the feeding 
  connection and the used cable will impact the length and it has to be adjusted during the test phase (NanoVNA).
</p><br>

<h3 class='scout-h3'>3. Tools</h3>
<p>
  The only tool I would recommend is a Vector Network Analyzer( VNA). That allows you to determine
  the antenna's Standing Wave Ratio (SWR) pretty accurately for a cheap price. The newer versions allow you 
  to connect the VNA to your laptop and use the browser as your output screen.
  </p><br>
  <h4><strong><u>Nano Vector Network Analyzer</u></strong></h4>
<p>
 Using the NanoVNA Edy555 with the latest firmware that allows you to measure frequncies from 50kHz to
 1.5GHz reliably. 
</p>
