<h3 class='scout-h3'>5. Build antenna</h3>
<p>The below picture shows how to bend the conductive wire so that it can be installed to the T-section
  of the antenna. When the antenna is connected mechanically and electrically the first time it is time to test. 
  Do not connect the antenna to your ham radio yet but start the initial testing with your device/tool that 
  can measuere the Standing Wave Ratio of your antenna. Would recommend to measure it with the cable length 
  you need and to use the same cable(feedline). <br>
  I am using the 'NanoVNA' which is accurate enough for me.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Some measurements:</strong>
  <ol type="I">
    <li>Measurement for the antenna arm holes: I drilled the holes in the PVC T-pipe  1&frac34;inch apart. That
  is around 44mm.</li>
  <li>In order to have the SWR lower than 2:1 and keeping the impedance of the wire and antenna around 50&ohm;
  the antenna arms for 2m were shortened to a length of 18&frac78; inches. The 70cm frequency was shortend 
  to 6<sup>2</sup>&frasl;<sub>8</sub> inches.</li>
</ol>
</p>
